Coming Up On the Calendar:

Thurs., March 19 Visit to Maharaja Sweets in Jackson Heights (tentative!)

Fri. March 20  HALF DAY (11:30 pick up)

Thurs., April 9 - Fri., April 17 NO SCHOOL (Spring Break)

Weds., April 22 Earth Day Plant Sale

Mon., April 27 - Fri., May 1 International Week

Weds., May 20 Field Day

Mon., May 25 NO SCHOOL (Memorial Day)

Weds., May 27 Field Day Rain Date


Dear Families,

     Thank you, as always, for the delightful conversations during Family
Conferences.  It has been wonderful to see you children grow this year-
intellectually, academically, socially, as well as find comfort and
confidence in the classroom!  Here is more about the week:

Irma Black Book Award

     On Wednesday we discussed the four books nominated for the Irma Black
Book Award.  We talked about genre (fiction, nonfiction, or a blend),
reflected on how the books made us feel, and reflected on the message of
each book.  Then, kids cast their ballots to vote for their preference. Our
choice for the award: The Most Terrible of All, a story about a monster who
meets his terrible match when he=E2=80=99s introduced to a baby monster.  W=
e=E2=80=99ll be
sending our class vote to Bank Street College of Education and they will
announce the official winner of the award in April.

Poetry!

     This week, we launched a unit on poetry!  We began the unit, by
picking a color (using a paint sample from the hardware store as
inspiration).  With each color, children wrote poems about things that are
related to the color or feelings they have when they look at the color.
For example, the color pink inspired mentions of cotton candy, green
brought up feelings of calm and happiness, and black gave us the shivers!

     On Tuesday, students chose everyday objects, such as feathers,
seashells, pinecones, and keys, game pieces from dominoes and chess, and
practiced looking at these objects through the eyes of a poet.  Some
children imagined the objects as animals, while other children thought of a
new use for an item or reimagined the item as something completely
different! We also talked about how poets write poetry a specific way (with
strategic placement of line breaks) so that it=E2=80=99s read in a way that=
 sounds
pleasing and musical.

Neighborhood Study

     This week, we took a look at the surveys you all completed from walks
in your neighborhood. We=E2=80=99ve been sharing information and charting a=
nd
graphing data.  One of our most interesting discussions was about the
languages we hear in our neighborhoods. As we took note of the various
languages we=E2=80=99d heard, we noticed the prevalence of some languages (=
Spanish,
Chinese/Mandarin/Cantonese), and the relative rarity of other languages
(Creole, for example).  We=E2=80=99ve also been mapping where we live on a =
subway
map.

     As we move forward with our study of neighborhoods, we=E2=80=99ll be p=
lanning
visits to neighborhoods around the city and visiting bakeries.  We thought
bakeries (and food!) might be a nice lens through which first graders might
experience different cultures. Our first visit will (tentatively) be to a
bakery called Maharaja Sweets in Jackson Heights.


     Lastly, we wanted to share these articles about talking to children
about Coronavirus.  We=E2=80=99ve heard some mention of it around the class=
room,
and have been taking extra measures to make sure everyone=E2=80=99s hands a=
re kept
clean (as well as our usual cleaning of classroom surfaces, doorknobs,
chairs, etc.)  When the topic comes up, we reassure kids about their own
safety, but want to also take precaution. Both these articles are worth a
read.  One from the New York Times Parenting Section
<https://parenting.nytimes.com/childrens-health/coronavirus-kids-talk?modul=
e=3Dptg-onsite-share&type=3Demail>

The other is from NPR.org.
<https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/28/809580453/just-for-ki=
ds-a-comic-exploring-the-new-coronavirus>

Photos from the past few weeks: https://gethomeroom.com/i/UBS4P3M4

Have a nice weekend,

Eleanor, Nita, and Shawna

